<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06270173 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06270173 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Olerud  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; BASEBALL; GAME; RESULT; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  John Olerud's three-run homer capped a six-run rally in the fifth inning andthe Toronto Blue Jays beat the California Angels 7-2 Wednesday in Anaheim,increasing their lead in the American League West to 2 1/2 games over Boston.;  The Red Sox lost ground for the second straight day without taking thefield. Their doubleheader with the host Baltimore Orioles was rained out andrescheduled for today.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  JAYS WIN; RED SOX WATCH RAIN  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  A.L. Roundup  </MEMO><TEXT>     Boston has 12 games left. Toronto has nine, including six against theWest-leading Minnesota Twins.;   Toronto, which lost four of its first sixgames on its West Coast trip, returns home for a three-game series againstMinnesota with a revived offense after winning two out of three against theAngels.;   Mark Langston (17-8) failed to hold a 2-1 lead Wednesday. He wasrocked for seven runs and eight hits in five innings. He had given up just sixearned runs in his previous 50 innings.;   Jimmy Key (16-11) also was shakyearly but settled down after the third and blanked the Angels over the nextfour innings.;   For the second game in a row, Angels Manager Buck Rodgerselected to intentionally walk a batter. And, again, the next hitter hit athree-run homer.;   Olerud hit a 2-and-0 fastball over the right-field fenceafter a walk to Candy Maldonado.; WHITE SOX 6, TWINS 1: Scott Fletcher drovein two runs with a double and sacrifice fly and Chicago kept Minnesota fromclinching a tie for the A.L. West title in Minneapolis.;   Minnesota's magicnumber remained at three. Any combination of Twins victories and White Soxlosses totaling three clinches the title for Minnesota.;   The Twins committeda season-high three errors, including two by catcher Brian Harper while tryingto throw out Lance Johnson attempting to steal.;   The Twins' Chuck Knoblauchextended his hitting streak to 20 games with a seventh-inning single.; OTHERGAMES: Cleveland's Doug Jones (4-7) remained perfect as a starting pitcher asthe Indians defeated the host Detroit Tigers 6-4. It was Jones' third majorleague start. . . . Nolan Ryan (12-6) gave up one run and three hits in eightinnings for his 314th victory and the Texas Rangers beat the host SeattleMariners 7-1. Ryan tied Gaylord Perry for 13th on the career victories list,four behind Phil Niekro. A.L. batting leader Julio Franco went 1 for 4,keeping his average at .341. Ken Griffey Jr. of the Mariners was hitless inthree at-bats against Ryan, striking out twice. Griffey's batting averagedropped to .332. . . . Roberto Kelly hit a three-run homer in the 11th inningas the New York Yankees beat the host Milwaukee Brewers 8-6.; A.L. East Race;THE LEAD; Toronto, by 2 1/2 games; Wednesday's scores; Toronto 7, California2; Boston at Baltimore (2), ppd., rain; Today's games; Boston (Roger Clemens17-8 and Joe Hesketh 11-4) at Baltimore (Dave Johnson 4-6 and Bob Milacki10-8), 9:15 a.m.;   Toronto is not scheduled  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910926  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  517  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday, September 26, 199100270173,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>